  "local_port": 39142,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Do Go-Back-N ARQ and Selective Repeat ARQ use cumulative acknowledgements or an acknowledgement for every individual packet?",
  "response": "To answer this question, let's examine how Go-Back-N ARQ and Selective Repeat ARQ handle acknowledgements:\n\n1. Go-Back-N ARQ:\n   - Go-Back-N ARQ uses cumulative acknowledgements.\n   - In this protocol, when a receiver successfully receives a packet, it sends an acknowledgement for all packets received up to and including that packet.\n   - The acknowledgement number indicates the next expected packet, effectively acknowledging all previous packets.\n   - If a packet is lost or corrupted, the receiver will continue to send acknowledgements for the last correctly received packet until the missing packet is retransmitted and received correctly.\n\n2. Selective Repeat ARQ:\n   - Selective Repeat ARQ typically uses individual acknowledgements for each packet.\n   - In this protocol, the receiver sends an acknowledgement for each correctly received packet, regardless of whether previous packets were received.\n   - This allows the sender to retransmit only the specific packets that were lost or corrupted, rather than retransmitting all subsequent packets.\n   - Some implementations of Selective Repeat may use a combination of individual and cumulative acknowledgements, but the core principle is to acknowledge each packet individually.\n\nIn summary:\n- Go-Back-N ARQ uses cumulative acknowledgements.\n- Selective Repeat ARQ typically uses individual acknowledgements for each packet, though some variations may incorporate cumulative acknowledgements as well.\n\nThese different acknowledgement strategies reflect the fundamental difference in how these two protocols handle packet loss and retransmission, with Go-Back-N being simpler but potentially less efficient, and Selective Repeat being more complex but potentially more efficient in terms of bandwidth usage.",
